snippet.textDisplay:
BALANCE=Conors whole approach to the fight game.

2 sides to one coin:

-Outer(Body)
-Mind(Inner)

The Body

If you develop one but not the other, you limit your success. The outer game Conor was smart enough to know he had to develop as a generalist in movement(hence his work with Ido Portal) that would give a huge base of support for his specialization which is fighting in MMA. Remember when Nate and others made fun of him for playing touch butt? They don't see the value hence their limitation.

The Mind.

I remember watching The Rise Of Conor McGregor on Youtube here and he just talked deeply about visualization and seeing/feeling yourself to BE your ideal. In this way of thinking one doesn't say "I WILL be the champ" one says "I AM the Champ!". You have to watch him talk about these topics to understand that he is obsessed with his mind. The PROBLEM here is power madness and he has already run into that and is feeling the repercussions.(Please ask yourself how you would do in the same position of money, power, drugs etc when you came from the humble background of being a fucking plumber. There IS no preparation for that.)

Which Conor?????

I keep hearing talk of if the "OLD" Conor shows up it's lights out and if not then BYE BYE! This is a false narrative!! The past is dead folks! Conor will NEVER be the same BUT will he show up with those elements in a good dynamic balance? If so, you get greatness. What is it that Conor knows that others dont? Simply this: If I obsess and you don't, I, through my own attention to detail, will see details you never will and capitalize on those little moments. Want a perfect example? Dan Hardy's fight analysis of Conor vs Alvarez shows the IQ and distance management and how the little things ARE the big things. Peace!

snippet.textDisplay:
Goldman Sachs Said to Receive Fed Warning on UFC Buyout Debt


Federal Reserve bank supervisors cautioned Goldman Sachs Group Inc. over risks in a debt deal it arranged to fund the $4 billion buyout of Ultimate Fighting Championship, according to people with knowledge of the matter.


The warning came in recent days as regulators continue their campaign to rein in risky lending practices by Wall Street’s biggest banks. Regulators have criticized deals that push a company’s debt load to more than six times its earnings. In the case of UFC, they’re focused on accounting adjustments that more than doubled the mixed martial arts promoter’s cash flow projections, said the people, who asked not to be identified because the matter is private.
